Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Soumyadip Mitra¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Prosper Loan data provided by Udacity. Prosper.com is a peer-to-peer lending marketplace. Borrowers make loan requests and investors contribute towards the loans of their choice.

We can see that many variables which are of interest to us have missing values which needs to be addressed.

APR is an important value, however, 25 missing BorrowerAPR values in the dataset. An easy fix is to caculate the missing APR as we know that BorrowerAPR = BorrowerRate + fee, where fee = BorrowerAPR - BorrowerRate. So we can caculate the median fee, then add them to the missing records.

In [10]:
borrower_fees = df["BorrowerAPR"] - df["BorrowerRate"]
borrower_fees.median()
Out[10]:
0.025019999999999987
In [11]:
df_sub["BorrowerAPR"].fillna(df["BorrowerRate"] + borrower_fees.median(), inplace=True)
# Check to make sure the cells are filled
df_sub["BorrowerAPR"].isnull().sum()
Out[11]:
0

8491 rows have missing debt to income ratio. However, those values can be easily replaced with 0.0

In [35]:
df_sub["DebtToIncomeRatio"].fillna(0.0, inplace = True)
df_sub["DebtToIncomeRatio"].isnull().sum()
Out[35]:
0

Also, the other variables ProsperRating (Alpha) and EmploymentStatus can't be replaced with other values and dropping those records will result in loss of information. Hence, I am just leaving them as Null.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • I am most interested in finding out which features are best for predicting the borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan. Also, I am interested in finding out the trends of the number of loans generated over the years as well as the income range of the borrowers of those loans.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • I think that the total loan amount will influence the APR of the loan. Also the borrowers stated monthly income, listing category, loan term, Prosper rating, DebtToIncomeRatio and Employment status will also have effects on the APR.

  • Also a better idea about the assets of the borrower would make it clear how the loans are rated.

Univariate Exploration¶

First I am interested in exploring the overall trend of the number of loans issued to borrowers by prosper loans over the years.

In [39]:
num_of_records = df_sub['ListingCreationDate'].groupby(df_sub.ListingCreationDate.dt.to_period("M")).agg('count')
In [40]:
num_of_records.plot(figsize=(10,6));

The number of loans with time is showing an increasing trend. We can also see that there are two steep drops in the number of loans borrowed, one between the year 2008 to 2009 which was the period of The Great Depression and the other at the end of 2012 which lasted for a shorter period of time. Also after further research it was known that the SEC imposed a cease and desist order on Prosper from the end of November 2008 till July 2009, which explains the steep fall in the number of loans issued.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • The distribution of borrowers APR looks slightly multimodal. Most of the values are at the range of 0.05 and 0.4.

  • The distribution of stated monthly income is severely right skewed, with most of stated monthly income less than 30k.

  • There are many 'Not Available' values in the category of listing that borrowers selected.

  • The Debt to Income Ratio is right skewed and has many high spikes at many values.

Overall, there are no unusual points and hence no need to perform any transformations as such.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • The distributions of Stated Monthly Income is highly right skewed. Most stated monthly incomes are less than 30k, but some of them are incredibly high, like greater than 100k and hence are likely to be outliers. Surprisingly, most of borrowers with greater than 100k monthly income only have loans less than 5k dollars. So, the very large stated monthly income may be made up. Overall, less than 0.3 percent borrowers have stated monthly income greater than 30k, these can be seemed as outlier for our analysis, so it is better to remove borrower records with income greater than 30k.

No other unlikely/unusual distributions were noticed and hence any other transformations were not performed.

Bivariate Exploration¶

For starters, let's look at the pairwise correlations present between features of interest in the data.

In [66]:

g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter, alpha=0.2);

Observations:-

  • The Loan original amount is positively correlated with the Stated monthly income and has a correlation coefficient value of 0.404, it makes sense since borrowers with more monthly income could loan more money.
  • The correlation coefficient of Borrower APR and Loan original amount is -0.323, the scatter plot also shows that these two variables are negatively correlated, which agrees with our hypothesis, that is the more the loan amount, the lower the APR.
  • From the correlation matrix it is observed that DebtToIncomeRatio does not have any significant correlations with other variables so we can ditch this variable for now and continue exploring with other quantitative and categorical variables.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The Borrower APR is negatively correlated with the Loan original amount, which mean the more the loan amount, the lower the APR. It also shows that the range of APR decreases with the increase of loan amount. The Listing Category does not seem to have a strong effect on the borrower APR. Other variables such as DebtToIncomeRatio and StatedMonthlyIncome does not seem to have much impact on Borrower APR.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Yes, the Loan original amount is positively correlated with the Stated monthly income, it makes sense since borrowers with more monthly income could loan more money. There is a interaction between prosper rating and term. Proportionally, there are more 60 month loans on B and C ratings. There is only 36 months loans for HR rating borrowers. Also Employed, self-employed and full time borrowers have more monthly income and loan amount than part-time, retired and not employed borrowers.

Multivariate Exploration¶

The main thing I want to explore in this part of the analysis is how the categorical variables (Prosper rating,Term and Employment Status) play into the relationship between Borrower APR, Loan original amount and Stated Monthly Income.

So, first let's look at how Borrower APR, Stated Monthly Income and Loan original amount correlate with the categorical variables.

In [94]:

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color);

Observations:-

  • Borrowers with better rating also have both larger monthly income and loan amount.
  • The figure shows that the loan amount is increased with the increase of loan term and it is obvious that best Prosper ratings are offered highr loan amounts.
  • Employed, self-employed and full time borrowers have more monthly income and loan amount than part-time, retired and not employed borrowers.

Since we observed above that both the variables Employment Status and Stated Monthly Income do not play a significant role in determining the Borrower APR, from now let's just focus on the other variables and exclude these from our analysis.

# Prosper rating effect on relationship of APR and loan amount
g=sns.FacetGrid(data=df_sub, height=5, col='ProsperRating (Alpha)', col_wrap=4)
g.map(sns.regplot, 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'BorrowerAPR', x_jitter=0.04, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.1});
g.add_legend();

Observations:-

  • The loan amount increases with better rating whereas the Borrower APR decreases with better rating.
  • The relationship between borrower APR and loan amount turns from negative to slightly positive when the Prosper ratings are increased from HR to AA. This may be because people with A or AA ratings tend to borrow more money, increasing APR could prevent them from borrowing even more and maximize the profit. But people with lower ratings tend to borrow less money, hence decreasing APR for higher loan amounts for them could encourage them to borrow more.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I extended my investigation of Borrower APR against all quantitative variables by looking at the impact of the other categorical variables. The multivariate exploration showed that Borrower APR decreases with the better Prosper rating. It means that the Prosper rating has a strong effect on borrower APR. Also, the borrowers with better Prosper rating have larger monthly income and loan amount. It was also observed that as the term value increases the loan amount also increases. The relationship between Borrower APR and Loan amount turns from negative to slightly positive when the Prosper ratings increased from HR to AA.

I then explored the Prosper rating and Term effects on borrower APR and loan amount. It shows that Borrower APR decreases with the increase of borrow Term for people with HR-C ratings. But for people with B-AA ratings, the APR increases with the increase of borrow term. Also, the Loan amount increases as the Term period increases and the variability of loan amount between terms also becomes larger.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

An interesting interaction is that the Borrower APR and Loan amount is negatively correlated when the Prosper ratings are HR, E, D, C and B but the correlation is turned to be positive when the ratings are A and AA. Another interesting thing is that the Borrower APR decreases with the increase in borrow term for people with HR-C raings. But for people with B-AA ratings, the APR increases with the borrow term.
